nificant figure, Toland counted queens, princes and government ministers as his friends and political associates. The book argues that Toland shaped the republican tradition after the Glorious Revolution into a practical and politically viable programme, focused not on destroying the monarchy, but on reforming public religion and the Church of England. It explores the connections between Toland's erudition and print culture, arguing that his intellectual project was aimed at compromising the authority of Christian 'knowledge' as much as the political power of the Church.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFreethinkerszEnglandvBiography. 0aRepublicanismzEuropexHistoryy18th century. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aChristian doctrine.  aGlorious Revolution.  aHanoverian succession.  aJohn Toland.  aSophia of Hanover.  acourt philosopher.  adivine revelation.  aecclesiastical establishment.  airreligious belief.  arepublican political thought.1 aChampion, Justin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526137630zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526137630zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526137630/original  a978-3-11-128363-0 Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA